ers `board` and a string `word`, return `true` *if* `word` *exists in the grid*.\n\nThe word can be constructed from letters of sequentially adjacent cells, where adjacent cells are horizontally or vertically neighboring. The same letter cell may not be used more than once.\n\n**Example 1:**\n\n[[img:leetcode_seed/assets/problems/0079-word-search/79-word2.jpg]]\n\nInput: board = [[\"A\",\"B\",\"C\",\"E\"],[\"S\",\"F\",\"C\",\"S\"],[\"A\",\"D\",\"E\",\"E\"]], word = \"ABCCED\"\nOutput: true\n\n**Example 2:**\n\n[[img:leetcode_seed/assets/problems/0079-word-search/79-word-1.jpg]]\n\nInput: board = [[\"A\",\"B\",\"C\",\"E\"],[\"S\",\"F\",\"C\",\"S\"],[\"A\",\"D\",\"E\",\"E\"]], word = \"SEE\"\nOutput: true\n\n**Example 3:**\n\n[[img:leetcode_seed/assets/problems/0079-word-search/79-word3.jpg]]\n\nInput: board = [[\"A\",\"B\",\"C\",\"E\"],[\"S\",\"F\",\"C\",\"S\"],[\"A\",\"D\",\"E\",\"E\"]], word = \"ABCB\"\nOutput: false\n\n**Constraints:**\n\n- `m == board.length`\n\n- `n = board[i].length`\n\n- `1 <= m, n <= 6`\n\n- `1 <= word.length <= 15`\n\n- `board` and `word` consists of only lowercase and uppercase English letters.\n\n**Follow up:** Could you use search pruning to make your solution faster with a larger `board`?","problemLink":"https://leetcode.com/problems/word-search/","problemName":"Word Search","problemNumber":79,"problemSlug":"word-search","schemaVersion":2,"sequenceIndex":79,"solutionApproaches":[]},{"assets":[],"categories":["Array","Two Pointers"],"constraintBlocks":[],"contentBlocks":[{"sequence":0,"text":"Given an integer array `nums` sorted in **non-decreasing order**, remove some duplicates [**in-place**](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/In-place_algorithm) such that each unique element appears **at most twice**. The **relative order** of the elements should be kept the **same**.\n\nSince it is impossible to change the length of the array in some languages, you must instead have the result be placed in the **first part** of the array `nums`. More formally, if there are `k` elements after removing the duplicates, then the first `k` elements of `nums` should hold the final result. It does not matter what you leave beyond the first `k` elements.\n\nReturn `k`* after placing the final result in the first *`k`* slots of *`nums`.\n\nDo **not** allocate extra space for another array. You must do this by **modifying the input array [in-place](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/In-place_algorithm)** with O(1) extra memory.\n\n**Custom Judge:**\n\nThe judge will test your solution with the following code:","type":"text"},{"sequence":1,"text":"int[] nums = [...]; // Input array\nint[] expectedNums = [...]; // The expected answer with correct length\n\nint k = removeDuplicates(nums); // Calls your implementation\n\nassert k == expectedNums.length;\nfor (int i = 0; i < k; i++) {\n    assert nums[i] == expectedNums[i];\n}","type":"code"},{"sequence":2,"text":"If all assertions pass, then your solution will be **accepted**.\n\n**Example 1:**","type":"text"},{"sequence":3,"text":"Input: nums = [1,1,1,2,2,3]\nOutput: 5, nums = [1,1,2,2,3,_]\nExplanation: Your function should return k = 5, with the first five elements of nums being 1, 1, 2, 2 and 3 respectively.\nIt does not matter what you leave beyond the returned k (hence they are underscores).","type":"code"},{"sequence":4,"text":"**Example 2:**","type":"text"},{"sequence":5,"text":"Input: nums = [0,0,1,1,1,1,2,3,3]\nOutput: 7, nums = [0,0,1,1,2,3,3,_,_]\nExplanation: Your function should return k = 7, with the first seven elements of nums being 0, 0, 1, 1, 2, 3 and 3 respectively.\nIt does not matter what you leave beyond the returned k (hence they are underscores).","type":"code"},{"sequence":6,"text":"**Constraints:**\n\n- `1 <= nums.length <= 3 * 10⁴`\n\n- `-10⁴ <= nums[i] <= 10⁴`\n\n- `nums` is sorted in **non-decreasing** order.","type":"text"}],"contentHtml":"","contentHtmlLocal":"","databaseEntry":{"categories":["Array","Two Pointers"],"createdAt":0,"difficulty":"Medium","lastRevisionAt":0,"problem":"Given an integer array `nums` sorted in **non-decreasing order**, remove some duplicates [**in-place**](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/In-place_algorithm) such that each unique element appears **at most twice**. The **relative order** of the elements should be kept the **same**.\n\nSince it is impossible to change the length of the array in some languages, you must instead have the result be placed in the **first part** of the array `nums`. More formally, if there are `k` elements after removing the duplicates, then the first `k` elements of `nums` should hold the final result. It does not matter what you leave beyond the first `k` elements.\n\nReturn `k`* after placing the final result in the first *`k`* slots of *`nums`.\n\nDo **not** allocate extra space for another array. You must do this by **modifying the input array [in-place](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/In-place_algorithm)** with O(1) extra memory.\n\n**Custom Judge:**\n\nThe judge will test your solution with the following code:\n\nint[] nums = [...]; // Input array\nint[] expectedNums = [...]; // The expected answer with correct length\n\nint k = removeDuplicates(nums); // Calls your implementation\n\nassert k == expectedNums.length;\nfor (int i = 0; i < k; i++) {\n    assert nums[i] == expectedNums[i];\n}\n\nIf all assertions pass, then your solution will be **accepted**.\n\n**Example 1:**\n\nInput: nums = [1,1,1,2,2,3]\nOutput: 5, nums = [1,1,2,2,3,_]\nExplanation: Your function should return k = 5, with the first five elements of nums being 1, 1, 2, 2 and 3 respectively.\nIt does not matter what you leave beyond the returned k (hence they are underscores).\n\n**Example 2:**\n\nInput: nums = [0,0,1,1,1,1,2,3,3]\nOutput: 7, nums = [0,0,1,1,2,3,3,_,_]\nExplanation: Your function should return k = 7, with the first seven elements of nums being 0, 0, 1, 1, 2, 3 and 3 respectively.\nIt does not matter what you leave beyond the returned k (hence they are underscores).\n\n**Constraints:**\n\n- `1 <= nums.length <= 3 * 10⁴`\n\n- `-10⁴ <= nums[i] <= 10⁴`\n\n- `nums` is sorted in **non-decreasing** order.","problemLink":"https://leetcode.com/problems/remove-duplicates-from-sorted-array-ii/","problemName":"Remove Duplicates from Sorted Array II","problemNumber":80,"revisionAnchorAt":0,"revisionCount":0,"revisionDates":[],"revisionPlanHours":[1,24,168,336,672],"solutionCode":"","testCases":"","updatedAt":0},"descriptionBlocks":[{"sequence":0,"text":"Given an integer array `nums` sorted in **non-decreasing order**, remove some duplicates [**in-place**](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/In-place_algorithm) such that each unique element appears **at most twice**. The **relative order** of the elements should be kept the **same**.\n\nSince it is impossible to change the length of the array in some languages, you must instead have the result be placed in the **first part** of the array `nums`. More formally, if there are `k` elements after removing the duplicates, then the first `k` elements of `nums` should hold the final result. It does not matter what you leave beyond the first `k` elements.\n\nReturn `k`* after placing the final result in the first *`k`* slots of *`nums`.\n\nDo **not** allocate extra space for another array. You must do this by **modifying the input array [in-place](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/In-place_algorithm)** with O(1) extra memory.\n\n**Custom Judge:**\n\nThe judge will test your solution with the following code:","type":"text"},{"sequence":1,"text":"int[] nums = [...]; // Input array\nint[] expectedNums = [...]; // The expected answer with correct length\n\nint k = removeDuplicates(nums); // Calls your implementation\n\nassert k == expectedNums.length;\nfor (int i = 0; i < k; i++) {\n    assert nums[i] == expectedNums[i];\n}","type":"code"},{"sequence":2,"text":"If all assertions pass, then your solution will be **accepted**.\n\n**Example 1:**","type":"text"},{"sequence":3,"text":"Input: nums = [1,1,1,2,2,3]\nOutput: 5, nums = [1,1,2,2,3,_]\nExplanation: Your function should return k = 5, with the first five elements of nums being 1, 1, 2, 2 and 3 respectively.\nIt does not matter what you leave beyond the returned k (hence they are underscores).","type":"code"},{"sequence":4,"text":"**Example 2:**","type":"text"},{"sequence":5,"text":"Input: nums = [0,0,1,1,1,1,2,3,3]\nOutput: 7, nums = [0,0,1,1,2,3,3,_,_]\nExplanation: Your function should return k = 7, with the first seven elements of nums being 0, 0, 1, 1, 2, 3 and 3 respectively.\nIt does not matter what you leave beyond the returned k (hence they are underscores).","type":"code"},{"sequence":6,"text":"**Constraints:**\n\n- `1 <= nums.length <= 3 * 10⁴`\n\n- `-10⁴ <= nums[i] <= 10⁴`\n\n- `nums` is sorted in **non-decreasing** order.","type":"text"}],"difficulty":"Medium","examples":[],"paidOnly":false,"problem":"Given an integer array `nums` sorted in **non-decreasing order**, remove some duplicates [**in-place**](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/In-place_algorithm) such that each unique element appears **at most twice**. The **relative order** of the elements should be kept the **same**.\n\nSince it is impossible to change the length of the array in some languages, you must instead have the result be placed in the **first part** of the array `nums`. More formally, if there are `k` elements after removing the duplicates, then the first `k` elements of `nums` should hold the final result. It does not matter what you leave beyond the first `k` elements.\n\nReturn `k`* after placing the final result in the first *`k`* slots of *`nums`.\n\nDo **not** allocate extra space for another array. You must do this by **modifying the input array [in-place](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/In-place_algorithm)** with O(1) extra memory.\n\n**Custom Judge:**\n\nThe judge will test your solution with the following code:\n\nint[] nums = [...]; // Input array\nint[] expectedNums = [...]; // The expected answer with correct length\n\nint k = removeDuplicates(nums); // Calls your implementation\n\nassert k == expectedNums.length;\nfor (int i = 0; i < k; i++) {\n    assert nums[i] == expectedNums[i];\n}\n\nIf all assertions pass, then your solution will be **accepted**.\n\n**Example 1:**\n\nInput: nums = [1,1,1,2,2,3]\nOutput: 5, nums = [1,1,2,2,3,_]\nExplanation: Your function should return k = 5, with the first five elements of nums being 1, 1, 2, 2 and 3 respectively.\nIt does not matter what you leave beyond the returned k (hence they are underscores).\n\n**Example 2:**\n\nInput: nums = [0,0,1,1,1,1,2,3,3]\nOutput: 7, nums = [0,0,1,1,2,3,3,_,_]\nExplanation: Your function should return k = 7, with the first seven elements of nums being 0, 0, 1, 1, 2, 3 and 3 respectively.\nIt does not matter what you leave beyond the returned k (hence they are underscores).\n\n**Constraints:**\n\n- `1 <= nums.length <= 3 * 10⁴`\n\n- `-10⁴ <= nums[i] <= 10⁴`\n\n- `nums` is sorted in **non-decreasing** order.","problemLink":"https://leetcode.com/problems/remove-duplicates-from-sorted-array-ii/","problemName":"Remove Duplicates from Sorted Array II","problemNumber":80,"problemSlug":"remove-duplicates-from-sorted-array-ii","schemaVersion":2,"sequenceIndex":80,"solutionApproaches":[]},{"assets":[],"categories":["Array","Binary Search"],"constraintBlocks":[],"contentBlocks":[{"sequence":0,"text":"There is an integer array `nums` sorted in non-decreasing order (not necessarily with **distinct** values).\n\nBefore being passed to your function, `nums` is **rotated** at an unknown pivot index `k` (`0 <= k < nums.length`) such that the resulting array is `[nums[k], nums[k+1], ..., nums[n-1], nums[0], nums[1], ..., nums[k-1]]` (**0-indexed**). For example, `[0,1,2,4,4,4,5,6,6,7]` might be rotated at pivot index `5` and become `[4,5,6,6,7,0,1,2,4,4]`.\n\nGiven the array `nums` **after** the rotation and an integer `target`, return `true`* if *`target`* is in *`nums`*, or *`false`* if it is not in *`nums`*.*\n\nYou must decrease the overall operation steps as much as possible.\n\n**Example 1:**","type":"text"},{"sequence":1,"text":"Input: nums = [2,5,6,0,0,1,2], target = 0\nOutput: true","type":"code"},{"sequence":2,"text":"**Example 2:**","type":"text"},{"sequence":3,"text":"Input: nums = [2,5,6,0,0,1,2], target = 3\nOutput: false","type":"code"},{"sequence":4,"text":"**Constraints:**\n\n- `1 <= nums.length <= 5000`\n\n- `-10⁴ <= nums[i] <= 10⁴`\n\n- `nums` is guaranteed to be rotated at some pivot.\n\n- `-10⁴ <= target <= 10⁴`\n\n**Follow up:** This problem is similar to [Search in Rotated Sorted Array](/problems/search-in-rotated-sorted-array/description/), but `nums` may contain **duplicates**. Would this affect the runtime complexity? How and why?","type":"text"}],"contentHtml":"","contentHtmlLocal":"","databaseEntry":{"categories":["Array","Binary Search"],"createdAt":0,"difficulty":"Medium","lastRevisionAt":0,"problem":"There is an integer array `nums` sorted in non-decreasing order (not necessarily with **distinct** values).\n\nBefore being passed to your function, `nums` is **rotated** at an unknown pivot index `k` (`0 <= k < nums.length`) such that the resulting array is `[nums[k], nums[k+1], ..., nums[n-1], nums[0], nums[1], ..., nums[k-1]]` (**0-indexed**). For example, `[0,1,2,4,4,4,5,6,6,7]` might be rotated at pivot index `5` and become `[4,5,6,6,7,0,1,2,4,4]`.\n\nGiven the array `nums` **after** the rotation and an integer `target`, return `true`* if *`target`* is in *`nums`*, or *`false`* if it is not in *`nums`*.*\n\nYou must decrease the overall operation steps as much as possible.\n\n**Example 1:**\n\nInput: nums = [2,5,6,0,0,1,2], target = 0\nOutput: true\n\n**Example 2:**\n\nInput: nums = [2,5,6,0,0,1,2], target = 3\nOutput: false\n\n**Constraints:**\n\n- `1 <= nums.length <= 5000`\n\n- `-10⁴ <= nums[i] <= 10⁴`\n\n- `nums` is guaranteed to be rotated at some pivot.\n\n- `-10⁴ <= target <= 10⁴`\n\n**Follow up:** This problem is similar to [Search in Rotated Sorted Array](/problems/search